text: DOI: 10.1002/cbdv.202100046 From arid, high desert soil samples collected near Bend, Oregon, 19 unique bacteria were isolated. Each strain was identified by 16S rRNA gene sequencing, and their organic extracts were tested for antibacterial and antiproliferative activities. Noteworthy, six extracts (30 %) exhibited strong inhibition resulting in less than 50 % cell proliferation in more than one cancer cell model, tested at 10 μg/mL. Principal component analysis (PCA) of LC/MS data revealed drastic differences in the metabolic profiles found in the organic extracts of these soil bacteria. In total, fourteen potent antibacterial and/or cytotoxic metabolites were isolated via bioactivity-guided fractionation, including two new natural products: a pyrazinone containing tetrapeptide and 7-methoxy-2,3- dimethyl-4H-chromen-4-one, as well as twelve known compounds: furanonaphthoquinone I, bafilomycin C1 and D, FD-594, oligomycin A, chloramphenicol, MY12-62A, rac-sclerone, isosclerone, tunicamycin VII, tunicamycin VIII, and (6S,16S)-anthrabenzoxocinone 1.264-C. Keywords: natural products, soil bacteria, actinomyces, antibiotics, cytotoxicity. Complex microbiota can be found in soils globally and their overall contribution to nutrient cycling, the health of soils, and impact on human society has become more evident in recent years.[1] Among the inhabitants, soil-dwelling bacteria have given us a remarkable diversity and unprecedented amount of bioactive small molecules.[2] A majority of currently used anti-infectives and many cytotoxic reagents, which enabled improved treatment of infections and cancers, have been found originally in bacteria or were inspired by their secondary metabolites.[2] Many of these privileged structures were found to be produced by filamentous, Gram-positive actinobacteria, with the genus Streptomyces being the most prolific and chemi- cally studied member.[3] Inspired by recent studies that Supporting information for this article is available on the WWW under https://doi.org/10.1002/cbdv.202100046

Chem. Biodiversity 2021, 18, e2100046 Chenxi Zhu,a, b Cassandra I. Lew,a George F. Neuhaus,a Donovon A. Adpressa,a Lev N. Zakharov,a Elizabeth N. Kaweesa,a, b Birte Plitzko,a and Sandra Loesgen*a, b Biodiversity, Bioactivity, and Metabolites of High Desert Derived Oregonian Soil Bacteria a Department of Chemistry, Oregon State University, Corvallis, Oregon 97331, USA, e-mail: sandra.loesgen@whitney.ufl.edu b Whitney Laboratory for Marine Bioscience, Department of Chemistry, University of Florida, St. Augustine, Florida 32080, USA showed high abundance of biosynthetic gene clusters and chemical diversity in bacteria derived from high altitude and arid soils in the US,[4 –6] we decided to explore soil bacteria from Oregon’s high desert. In total, 19 bacterial strains were isolated, and identified via 16S rRNA fingerprinting techniques. Along with the culturable bacterial species diversity, we were also interested in the chemical and bioactivity potential among these isolates. All bacteria were grown in malt- based media and the organic extracts were tested against five cancer cell lines and against four microbial human pathogens. Half the extracts were active in these bioactivity assays and fourteen metabolites were isolated and characterized. This case study corrobo- rates that the Oregonian high desert is a promising place for bacterial exploration and many potent anti- biotics and cytotoxic compounds can be sourced from local soils. © 2021 Wiley-VHCA AG, Zurich, Switzerland Figure 1. Presented here are 19 bacterial strains (Figure 1) that were isolated from four soil collection sites close to Bend, Oregon. Once isolated, all bacteria were grown on malt-based agar plates, with visible colony forma- tion in about 5 –7 days. Only Actinophytocola oryzae (LL2-4E) took 6–8 weeks to establish visible growth. Each strain presented a unique phenotype, for exam- ple Amycolatopsis saalfeldensis (LL2-4B) formed white spores and released a characteristic red pigment into the agar; Paraburkholderia fungorum (LL2-4C-B) is a non-sporulating, Gram-negative bacterium with slimy, black-brown colonies; and the spores of Streptomyces sparsogenes (LT2-5) changed color from white to pale Chem. Biodiversity 2021, 18, e2100046 yellow to finally black-brown within two weeks. bor-joining tree (Figure 2).[9] Of the isolated bacteria, 15 belong to the phylum actinobacteria, with a majority being Streptomyces spp. (58 %). Arthrobacter agilis, Mycolicibacterium hodleri, and Amycolatopsis saalfeldensis were also isolated. Three Gram-negative proteobacteria were isolated: Pseudomonas trivialis, Paraburkholderia fungorum, and Mesorhizobium hua- kuii. Overall, the taxonomic assignments were helpful to compare phenotypes, bioactivities, and metabolites, but it should be noted that the presented species designation is tentative, solely based on sequencing ~ 1200 bp of the 16S rRNA region, not full genome sequences. Prof. Brian Murphy and team recently developed IDBac, a pipeline to simplify the bacterial prioritization process for chemical screening.[10,11] One feature is the hierarchical clustering based on MALDI-TOF-MS pro- tein spectra, offering a different approach to assess the taxonomic diversity of bacterial colonies.[12] Eleven strains were picked as a test case and subjected to MALDI-TOF-MS analysis via the IDBac pipeline and software which revealed similar phylogenic relation- ship compared to the 16S rRNA fingerprinting (Sup- porting Information Figure 1). Streptomyces sparsogenes (LT2-5), with its spore color-changing phenotype, is the most distant to the other Streptomyces. Its closest Figure 2. The clustering of Streptomyces hundungensis (LL2-5B), Streptomyces malachitospinus (LL2-4A), and Streptomyces resistomycificus (CL12-5) also agreed with our analysis based on 16S rRNA DNA fingerprinting. In summary, it was exciting to see that the IDBAc pipeline with its MALDI-TOF-MS methodology produced com- parable taxonomic information for a set of 11 strains in a fraction of the time required in traditional 16S rRNA fingerprinting. Bacteria were cultured in malt-based media for four weeks. Organic extracts of each bacterial culture were prepared at a concentration of 10 mg/mL in DMSO as stock solution for bioactivity assays. Cytotoxic activities were evaluated at 10 μg/mL against five cancer cell lines: human colorectal carcinoma, human breast adenocarcinoma, melanoma, prostate cancer, and lung following established procedures.[13– 15] Six cancer extracts (30 % of all samples) showed strong inhibition with more than 50 % cell growth inhibition in at least one cancer cell lines (Figure 3A). Dereplication and Identification of Metabolites For each bioactive extract, a 16 L liquid culture of the respective strain was grown and extracted to enable compound isolation. Antibacterial/cytotoxic testing was used to guide chromatographic separation steps. Using this approach, twelve known metabolites and two new natural products were isolated from bioactive extracts. The structure of 6 was identified based on UV, HR-MS, and NMR spectroscopic data from a recently Supporting Information).[32] Oligomycin A is a potent inhibitor of ATP synthase and a strong cytotoxic agent to most human cells, and a recent study found inhibition of K- Ras plasma membrane localization in colorectal carci- noma cell In our study, CL18-4D extracts impairs highly metabolically active melanoma cells lines tested, more than the other mammalian cell which could be attributed to the ATPase inhibitor.

Liquid chromatography mass spectrometry (LC/MS) data derived from all bacterial organic extracts was subjected to untargeted analysis, here a principal component analysis (PCA) was used to illustrate metabolomic differences among Oregonian isolates (Supporting Information Figure S51A). The data visual- izes the chemical diversity found in the isolated bacteria, which aided in strain prioritization and compound isolation efforts. The PCA plot of bacteria isolated in 2014 showed both Streptomyces lucensis CL16-5B and CL16-5C clustering together and both are producing FD-594. The unidentified bacterium (CL16- 4) and Streptomyces avermitilis (CL18-4D) grouped closely together and both produced macrolide anti- biotics bafilomycin C1/D and oligomycin A. Interest- ingly, Streptomyces (CL12-5), which produced furanonaphthoquionone I and 2, were the most distant in its chemotype compared to the other strains in the PCA analysis. Here, no overlapping patterns were observed, somewhat unique chemical profiles in each extract. For example, only Streptomyces hundungensis (LL2-5B) produced the glycosylated nucleoside antibiotics tunicamycins and is seen distant from other strains in the PCA, while the two anthrabenzoxocinone producing strains, Strepto- myces sparsogenes (LT2-5) and Streptomyces paucispor- eus (LL2-3) clustered closer together. Noteworthy, extracts containing active metabolites were placed far from the center in the PCA plot which indicates that these strains exhibit a higher chemical diversity, based on the amount and uniqueness of mass spectrometric features, with specialized, species specific secondary metabolites.

In this study, the biodiversity and chemodiversity of 19 high desert derived Oregonian soil strains was ex- plored by phylogenetic analysis via 16S rRNA sequenc- ing, and phenotypic assays for cell viability and anti- biotic activity. Prioritization of strains for chemical analysis was made easy by the IDBac pipeline to analyze MALDI-based TOF-MS data, and LC/MS-based metabolomics approaches. Four bacterial pathogens and five human cancer cell lines were used to screen the organic extracts of all isolates. Over 50 % of extracts (10 out of 19 strains) showed potent anti- bacterial activity at a single dose of 125 μg/mL and/or Chem. Biodiversity 2021, 18, e2100046

cytotoxic property at dose of 10 μg/mL. Three extracts exhibited antibacterial properties without associated cytotoxicity. Known antibacterial or cytotoxic agents, including the broad antibiotic chloramphenicol, mac- rolide antibiotics bafilomycin C1/D and oligomycin A, glycosylated natural products tunicamycin VII/VIII, FD- 594 were isolated from this small panel of Oregonian bacteria. The activity profile observed in the extracts and fractions can be attributed to the isolated metabolites, but we cannot exclude that minute quantities or metabolites invisible in our UV and mass spectrometric screen were missed. Bioactivity- and chemical-guided isolation yielded the discovery of two new natural products, a tetrapeptide 2 and 7-meth- oxy-2,3-dimethyl-4H-chromen-4-one (11), along with twelve known antibiotic and/or cytotoxic compounds. For compound MY12-62A (8), the absolute configura- tion was established for the first time by comparative analysis of experimental and TD-DFT derived spectral data. 2, from Streptomyces resistomycificus (CL12-5), did not show any bioactivity in either antibacterial or cytotoxicity assays, while 11, from Paraburkholderia fungorum (LL2-4C-B), was slightly active against methi- cillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus (MRSA) at 10 μM with 65 % bacterial cell survival.

Optical rotations were measured on a JASCO P-1010 polarimeter. Circular dichroism (CD) and UV measure- ments were recorded using a JASCO J-815 spectropo- larimeter. Infrared (IR) spectra were recorded on a Thermo Scientific Nicolet IR100 FT-IR spectrometer. NMR spectra were acquired on a Bruker Avance III 500 MHz or Bruker Avance III 700 MHz spectrometer, equipped with a 5 mm TXI probe or 13C cryoprobe, respectively, with the residual solvent used as internal standards: (D6)acetone (δH 2.05; δC 29.82), CDCl3 (δH 7.26; δC 77.06), (D6)DMSO (δH 2.50; δC 39.50), and CD3OD (δH 3.31; δC 49.00).[50] Low-resolution ESI-MS mass spectra were recorded on Agilent 1100 series LC with MSD 1946. High-resolution ESI-MS spectra were recorded on an Agilent 6545 LC/Q-TOF-MS. Vacuum liquid column chromatography (VLCC) was performed using silica gel 60 (70 –230 mesh, Silicycle), with seven mobile phase gradients of dichloromethane/methanol (v/v 99 : 1, 30 : 1, 15 : 1, 9 : 1, 3 : 1, 1 : 1, 0 : 1). Analytical thin layer chromatography (TLC) was performed on a pre-coated silica gel 60 F254 plates (Eppendorf), visualized by UV (254 and 360 nm) and by spraying with anisaldehyde solution followed by heating at 80 °C. A Teledyne ISCO Combi-Flash Companion sys- tem was used for automated flash chromatography using silica gel. Analytical HPLC was performed using an Agilent 1100 HPLC with a Phenomenex kinetex C- 18 column (5 μm × 150 mm × 4.6 mm) and a gradient elution with ultra-pure H2O and MeCN with 0.05 % formic acid in each solvent at a flow rate of 0.8 mL/ min. Additionally, a Chiralcel® OD-H column 10 μm × 250 mm × 4.6 mm (at a flow rate of 0.7 mL/min) was used to separate racemic sclerone. Semi- and prepara- tive HPLC was performed using an Agilent 1100 and 1260 HPLC system with a Phenomenex kinetex C-18 column (5 μm × 150 mm × 10 mm, at a flow rate of 4.0 mL/min) and a Phenomenex Luna C-18 column (5 μm × 250 mm × 21 mm, at a flow rate of 20.0 mL/ min). All samples were filtered through a 0.45 μm nylon filter before LC/MS and HPLC analysis. General reagents were purchased from Sigma-Aldrich Corp., Fisher Scientific, and VWR International. Media Conditions and Isolation of Soil Bacteria

All cultures were fermented in either M2 media (malt extract (10 g/L), yeast extract (4 g/L), glucose (4 g/L), pH 7.0 prior to sterilization) or R2 A (purchased from BD Difco™). Media with antifungal drugs to prevent fungal and yeast growth during the isolation process was prepared by the addition of sterile solutions of nystatin (25 mg/L) and cycloheximide (50 mg/L) added post-sterilization. For solid growth conditions, 15 g agar per liter was added to culture media prior to sterilization. Four soil samples were collected from two different sites close to Bend, OR, on June 2014 (43°59’14’’ N, 121°20’11’’ W) and June 2016 (44°18’41’’ N, 121°25’30’’ W; 43°59’14’’ N, 121°22’12’’ W). Soil samples were placed in sterile 50 mL plastic Whirl-Pak bags and kept cool until processing within 72 h. Collected soil samples were dried overnight in a laminar-flow biocabinet.[51] 0.5 –1.0 g of soil was added to 10 mL of autoclaved ultra-pure water and serial diluted 1 : 10. and Dilutions Chem. Biodiversity 2021, 18, e2100046 1 : 1,000,000 were used to inoculate high and low nutrient media agar plates (medium M2 and R2A) using a sterile applicator loop (VWR). Inoculated plates were incubated at 28 °C for up to 12 weeks. Any well-separated bacterial colonies, as observed by eye, were removed from the original isolation plates and sub-cultured on M2 agar plates. Most of the Gram-positive strains possessed morpho- logical class characteristic actinobacteria.[52] All strains were grouped according to colony color, morphology, and pigment production, and subjected to phylogenetic analysis. All strains were cryopreserved with 15 % of glycerol in liquid media at (cid:0) 80 °C. Organic Extract Preparation

Pure colonies were picked and grown for 5 –7 days on M2 agar. One 2 cm2 piece of agar with mycelium was used to inoculate 50 mL of M2 media for 4 –7 days as seed culture, this culture was then used to inoculate 500 mL of M2 liquid culture. All bacterial strains were grown at 28 °C on an orbital shaker at 120 rpm for 2 –4 weeks. Bacterial cultures were checked for purity via a clean streak, and then, the broth was adjusted to pH 5 and extracted with equal volumes of ethyl acetate three times. The organic layer was collected, dried over magnesium sulfate, and concentrated under vacuum. For large scale extraction, mycelium was filtered off, and the supernatant absorbed on XAD-7 resin. The extract was recovered from the resin using acetone and methanol washes, respectively, after rinsing with an equal volume of DI water. The separated mycelium/cell mass was sonicated in acetone for 20 min and combined with the XAD resin derived extract after testing by TLC that the metabolic profile of cells and supernatant was similar. Taxonomic Analyses of Bacteria For taxonomic analysis, cells were grown and collected by centrifugation. The cell pellet was frozen and crushed in liquid nitrogen and incubated with lysozyme solution at 37 °C for 30 min and then, with 3 μl of proteinase K and 10 % (w/v) sodium dodecyl sulfate (SDS) at 55 °C for 30 min. DNA was extracted from a phenol-chloroform solution (v/v 1 : 1) by centrifugation at 12,000 rpm for 5 min. The 16S rRNA loci were amplified from genomic DNA using PCR protocols using the following primers: 8f (5’-AGAGTTTGATCMTGGCTCAG) (5’- ACGGCTACCTTGTTACGACTT),[53] (both purchased from © 2021 Wiley-VHCA AG, Zurich, Switzerland

Integrated DNA Technologies, IDT). The 50 μL PCR mixture contained 20 to 40 ng of DNA template, 10 pmol of each primer, 25 μL of MangoMixTM (pur- chased from Bioline, UK) containing MangoTaqTM DNA polymerase, dNTPs, red and orange reference dyes and Mg2 +. The PCR program consisted of 30 cycles at 94 °C for 30 seconds, 55 °C for 30 seconds, and 72 °C for 90 seconds followed by a final extension step at 72 °C for 10 min. Amplified DNA products were examined and purified by agarose gel electrophoresis using the Pure- LinkTM quick gel extraction kit (purchased from Invitro- gen by life technologies, Germany) according to the manufacturer’s instructions. Sequencing was carried out using an ABI 3730 capillary sequence machine at OSU’s CGRB Core Facilities with primers 8f and 1513r. All nucleotide sequences were analyzed and com- pared to sequences within the NCBI database (http:// www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/)[7] using the Basic Local Align- (BLAST)[7] or EzBiocloud 16S ment Search Tool database.[8] Partial 16S rRNA gene sequences can be found in the Supporting Information. A phylogenetic tree was created with MEGA7.[9] The evolutionary history was inferred using the Neighbour-Joining method.[54] The optimal tree with the sum of branch length = 1.01839152 is shown (next to the branches). The evolutionary distances were computed using the Maximum Composite Likelihood method.[54]

In collaboration with Prof Brian Murphy (UIC), bacterial colonies were subjected to their IDBac pipeline.[10,11] For matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization time-of- flight mass spectrometry (MALDI-TOF-MS) analysis, the bacteria were streaked on M2 agar plates individually and grown for 12 days. Single bacterial colonies were picked for in situ analysis by MALDI-TOF-MS for taxonomic protein markers.[12] Converted data results was imported and analyzed in the freely-available following published guidelines.[11] IDBac software, IDBac provides the hierarchical clustering of protein spectra and places bacterial isolates into putative genus- and species-level groups. Principal Component Analysis (PCA) of Extract LC/MS Data Liquid chromatography mass spectrometry data de- rived from all bacterial organic extracts was subjected to principal component analysis (PCA). Organic ex- tracts, prepared at 10 mg/mL in MeCN, were tested on Chem. Biodiversity 2021, 18, e2100046

analytical LC/MS system using a gradient elution (10– 100 % MeCN with 0.05 % formic acid) and samples were tested in triplicates. Peak lists were modified and exported from MZmine,[55] and PCA plots were gen- erated with MetaboAnalyst 4.0.[56 –58] Bacteria isolated from the 2014 collection and the 2016 collection were analyzed separately. The mass detection was per- formed using a centroid algorithm with a noise level of 1000. The chromatogram builder had the following parameters: minimum time span of 0.1 min, minimum intensity of the highest data of 2000 and a tolerance of m/z 0.05 or 250 ppm. A smoothing filter was applied with the value of 25. Peak deconvolution was preformed using the local minimum search algorithm with the following parameters: chromatographic threshold of 99 %, search minimum in retention time is 40 min, minimum relative height of 10.0 % minimum, absolute height is 2000. Samples of the same treat- ment or phenotype were aligned separately using the join alignment, gap filling, and duplicate peak filter algorithms. The join alignment had the following parameters: tolerance of m/z 0.05 or 10.0 ppm, m/z weight 20, 3.0 retention time tolerance, and retention time weight 10. A duplicate peak filter was applied with the following: tolerance of m/z 0.1 or 25.0 ppm and 0.4 min (absolute) retention time tolerance. The files were exported as a *.csv file containing all peaks observed and references based on the m/z values and retention times. The *.csv file was then cleaned up with abundant ions (m/z) found in the media blanks and solvent blanks. The data was uploaded to Metaboanalyst 4.0 website (https://www.metaboana- lyst.ca/).[56–58] Missing values in the data were replaced by a small value of half the minimum positive value in the original data. Interquartile range and log trans- formations were applied in data filtering and data transformation. Single Dose Cell Viability Assay

Inhibition of cell viability of extracts was evaluated following established protocols[13– 15] against five can- cer cell lines models: human colorectal carcinoma model (HCT-116, ATCC CCL-247), human breast adeno- carcinoma cell lines (MCF-7, ATCC HTB-22), melanoma (SK-Mel-5, ATCC HTB70), prostate cancer (PC3, ATCC CRL-1435), and lung cancer (A-549, ATCC CCL-185). Cellular cytotoxicity was determined measuring the reduction of the tetrazolium salt MTT (3-(4,5-dimeth- ylthiazol-2-yl)-2,5-diphenyltetrazolium bromide) by metabolically active cells via absorbance at 550 nm using a Biotek Synergy 96-well plate reader. Metabolic © 2021 Wiley-VHCA AG, Zurich, Switzerland activity of vehicle-treated cells (0.1 % DMSO) was defined as 100 % cell growth. Etoposide (250 μM) was used as a positive control. Organic extracts and fractions were dosed at 10 μg/ml to each well for single dose cellular cytotoxicity analysis. Single Dose Antibacterial Assay All extracts were tested for antibacterial activity in cell- based assays following established protocols.[16 –18] The antibacterial activity was evaluated against two Gram-positive pathogens including Enterococcus fae- cium (ATCC 49032) and methicillin-resistant Staph- ylococcus aureus (ATCC BAA-41) as well as two Gram- negative pathogens: Pseudomonas aeruginosa (ATCC 15442) and Escherichia coli (ATCC 8739). Vancomycin and chloramphenicol were used as positive controls in Gram-positive and Gram-negative pathogens, respec- tively. Tested extracts and antibiotic controls were dosed at 125 μg/mL. Bacterial growth rates were measured by absorbance at 620 nm using Biotek Synergy 96-well plate reader. Advanced Marfey’s Analysis[24,25]

Approximately 0.2 mg of tetrapeptide 2 was hydro- lyzed with 6 N HCl at 110 °C for 24 h, then evaporated to dryness and reconstituted in 100 μL of MeOH/H2O (v/v 1 : 1) solution. 100 μL of FDLA solution in acetone (0.1 % w/v) and 20 μL of 1 M NaHCO3 were added to the hydrolysate and heated to 40 °C for 1 h. The solution was cooled down to room temperature, and then, neutralized with 2 N HCl and evaporated to dryness.[24,25] The residue was resuspended in 100 μL of MeCN/H2O (v/v 1 : 1) solution, and then, analyzed by LC/MS (column 1 with a gradient method from 35 % to 50 % MeCN). Diffraction intensities for compound 11 were collected at 173 K on a Bruker Apex2 DUO CCD diffractometer using CuKα radiation, λ = 1.54178 Å. Absorption correc- tion was applied by SADAB.[59] Space group was determined based on intensity statistics. Structure was solved by direct methods and Fourier techniques and refined on F2 using full matrix least-squares proce- dures. All non-H atoms were refined with anisotropic thermal parameters. H atoms in the aromatic rings were found on the residual density map and refined with isotropic thermal parameters. Methyl H atoms were refined in calculated positions without restric- Chem. Biodiversity 2021, 18, e2100046 tions on rotation around the C(cid:0) C bonds, HFIX 138 in SHELXL.[60] All calculations were performed by the Bruker SHELXL-2014/7 package.[60]

ECD Computational details for MY12-62A (8). Initial conformational analysis was performed in Spartan[61] using the MMFF Merck molecular force field and random rotor conformational search with 100 con- formers for the (R) enantiomer. Density functional theory calculations were performed using the Gaussian 09 package.[36] The generated conformer sets was subjected to gas phase QM geometry optimizations and frequency calculations at B3LYP/6-31 + G before solvated geometry optimizations at M062X/TZVP with IEFPCM in methanol. ECD spectra were calculated by the TDDFT methodology using the following basis sets: ωB97X/def2-TZVP (UV shift of 14 nm and a σ value of 0.70 eV) utilizing IEFPCM in methanol, CAM- B3LYP/TZVP with IEFPCM in methanol (UV shift of 11 nm and a σ value of 0.66 eV) and M062X/def2-TZVP (UV shift of 9 nm and a σ value of 0.62 eV) utilizing IEFPCM in methanol. ECD spectra were simulated using SpecDis 1.71.[62] ECD spectra of (S) enantiomer were generated by reflection of (R) enantiomer. tetrapeptide (2): conformers were generated for computation of ECD spectra by a MCMM search at the MMFF level in Spartan 14[61] for diastereoisomers of 2. Conformers below 5 kcal/mol were carried forward into a QM geometry optimization at the PCM-B97D/def2-TZVP level in ORCA. Conformers accounting for greater than 2 % of the Boltzmann distribution were ECD Computational details for © 2021 Wiley-VHCA AG, Zurich, Switzerland subjected to TDDFT calculations at the PCM-ωB97xD/ def2-TZVP level. Computationally generated UV spec- tra were matched to the experimental spectra using SpecDis 1.71[62] and the σ and wavelength correction were applied to the computational derived ECD spectra.
